   <br/>
   <table bgcolor="#FFFFFF" border="0" bordercolor="#FFFFFF" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" valign="top" width="850">
    <tr>
     <th align="right" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" height="1587" scope="col" valign="top" width="400">
      <table bgcolor="#FFFFFF" border="0" bordercolor="#FFFFFF" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" valign="top" width="850">
       <tr>
        <td bgcolor="#C4D6E6" rowspan="2" valign="top" width="199">
         <h4>
          <strong>
           The Senate is a University-wide legislature,  representing faculty, students, and other constituencies. It makes policy on a  range of issues that affect the entire University or more than one school,  including educational programs and priorities, the budget, academic freedom and  tenure, the conduct of research, the libraries, information technology,  Columbia's external relations, student sexual misconduct, rules governing  political demonstrations, and the welfare of faculty, students, and research  officers. Trustee concurrence is required for acts of the  Senate.
          </strong>
         </h4>
         <h4>
          The Senate has 108 voting seats, with 63 reserved for faculty, 24 for students, 6 for officers of research,
          <br/>
          2 each for administrative staff, librarians, and alumni, and 9 for senior administrators including the president, who chairs monthly plenaries.
         </h4>
         <hr/>
         <h2 align="center">
          JOIN OUR MAILING LIST!
         </h2>
         <p align="center">
          Click
          <a href="http://eepurl.com/bAdBiT">
           here
          </a>
          to receive email announcements of plenary meetings and updates on Senate activities.
         </p>
         <h3 align="center">
         </h3>
         <p>
         </p>
        </td>
        <th align="right" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" height="1503" scope="col" valign="top" width="400">
         <p align="left">
          <img height="529" src="images/index_photos/lancet_women.jpg" title="SOPHIE MCKAY KNIGHT" width="400"/>
         </p>
         <p align="left">
          We are very pleased to share with you
          <strong>
           "Achieving women's equity in academic medicine: challenging the standards,"
          </strong>
          published in The Lancet theme issue "Advancing Women in science, medicine and global health." This article draws on the Commission on the Status of Women's recent study of the advancement of women at the Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons and builds on its earlier work on this issue, including the 2015 study into the advancement of women through the academic ranks of the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences.
         </p>
         <p align="left">
          All content is available (with registration) at
          <a href="https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/home">
           https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/home
          </a>
          and you will find the livestreams for both the London and New York launches on the #LancetWomen landing page:
          <a href="https://www.thelancet.com/lancet-women">
           https://www.thelancet.com/lancet-women
          </a>
          .
         </p>
         <hr/>
         <p align="left">
          <img height="351" src="images/index_photos/sac_at_plenary_2-8-19.jpg" title="photograph by Jessica Raimi" width="400"/>
         </p>
         <p align="left">
          At the Senate plenary on February 8,  Sens.
          <strong>
           Zoha Qamar
          </strong>
          (SEAS undergraduate, center) and
          <strong>
           Danielle Resheff
          </strong>
          (CC, right), along with
          <strong>
           Aja Johnson
          </strong>
          (left) of the Columbia College Student Council, presented a
          <a href="/archives/plenary/18-19/plenary_documents/sanitary_items_at_columbia_20190208.pdf">
           proposal
          </a>
          from the student councils of the College, SEAS and GS to provide free feminine sanitary products in bathrooms across campus.
         </p>
